      "text": "Identify the false statements regarding the amyloid.\n\n1) It is a proteoglycan.\n\n2) It is a misfolded protein seen intracellularly.\n\n3) They show cross-β-pleated sheet conformation in light microscopy.\n\n4) 95% of amyloid consists of fibril proteins.\n\n5) It appears as an amorphous, basophilic, hyaline, extracellular substance.",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "1,2,3"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "2,5"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "3,4"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "2,3,5"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 3,
      "solution": "<p><strong>CORRECT ANSWER:</strong> <strong>D) 2,3,5</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>EXPLANATION:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Amyloid is defined as a <strong>proteoglycan</strong> and a <strong>misfolded protein</strong>, seen <strong>extracellularly</strong>. <strong>(Statements 1 and 2)</strong></li>\n\t<li>The presence of abundant charged sugar groups in these adsorbed proteins gives the deposits <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3b007026bd16927771997ae809b603\">staining</span> characteristics that were thought to resemble <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"24511b2ef716927771990798c3d939\">starch</span> (amylose). Therefore, the deposits were called amyloid</li>\n\t<li>95% of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> consists of <strong>fibril</strong> proteins, with the remaining 5% being glycosaminoglycans (dermatan <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"535af9a2181692777199309af44d24\">sulfate</span> and heparan sulfate) and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a0e40688fa169277719572bdb48c92\">plasma</span> proteins, notably <strong>serum <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> P</strong>. <strong>(Statement 4)</strong></li>\n\t<li>Physical nature of amyloid:\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li>Light <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51df8cdfc91692777192aa76f4de51\">microscopy</span> with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b35c67a8d316927771883ab652b328\">H & E</span> stains: <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">Amyloid</span> is an <strong>amorphous</strong>, <strong>eosinophilic</strong>, <strong>hyaline</strong>, and <strong>extracellular </strong>substance. <strong>(Statement 5)</strong></li>\n\t\t<li>Electron microscopy: All types of amyloid, regardless of clinical setting or chemical composition, consist of <strong>continuous, nonbranching fibrils</strong> with a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"afb15e4a331692777186e495b370a1\">diameter</span> of approximately 7.5 to 10 nm.</li>\n\t\t<li>X-ray <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1ab23807771692777185b9e3f5a412\">crystallography</span> and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"82df9c600116927771907b7977a3b4\">infrared</span> spectroscopy: Characteristic <strong>cross-β-pleated sheet </strong>conformation is responsible for the distinctive Congo-red <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3b007026bd16927771997ae809b603\">staining</span> and apple-green <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"87ae867513169277718388f8442cf9\">birefringence</span> of the amyloid. <strong>(Statement 3)</strong>\n\t\t<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"Nephron\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"CC BY-SA 3.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Renal_amyloidosis_-_2_-_very_high_mag.jpg\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"1107\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/06lRu5udvdKjcP8RaDVo1737015827.png\" width=\"1999\" /></p>\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>",
