    {
      "text": "A 65-year-old male with a history of multiple myeloma in remission presents with fatigue, weight loss, and abdominal discomfort. He reports early satiety and a palpable firm mass in the left upper quadrant. Which finding is not associated with this condition?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Sago's spleen"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Lardaceous spleen"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Carpal tunnel syndrome"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Nephritic syndrome"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 3,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer:</strong> <strong>D) Nephritic Syndrome</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<p>The given clinical scenario of a male with <strong>fatigue</strong>, <strong>weight loss</strong>, <strong>abdominal discomfort</strong>, <strong>swelling in the left upper quadrant</strong> (splenomegaly), and a <strong>history of multiple myeloma</strong> is suggestive of <strong>AL amyloidosis</strong>. Nephritic syndrome is not associated with this condition, rather, <strong>nephrotic syndrome</strong> can be seen.</p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li><strong>Sago spleen:</strong> It refers to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> deposits largely limited to the splenic follicles (white pulp), producing tapioca-like granules on gross inspection.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Lardaceous spleen:</strong> This involves <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> deposition in the walls of the splenic sinuses and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"67e237a57c16927771859803f93ab3\">connective</span> tissue framework in the<strong> red pulp.</strong></li>\n\t<li><strong>Carpal tunnel syndrome:</strong> Can be associated with amyloidosis, especially in patients on long-term <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"6ba3fb0ce51692777188eaf7843351\">hemodialysis</span> due to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> deposition in the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"c8a21e01261692777183ccc5569251\">carpal</span> ligament.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Nephrotic syndrome:</strong> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"959f3344b116927771815235718f3d\">Amyloidosis</span> more commonly causes <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7063996c3816927771930f70c92eb4\">nephrotic</span> syndrome (not nephritic) due to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1ad1e71a4a1692777188853097f685\">glomerular</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> deposition. Nephritic syndrome is characterised by inflammation, <strong>while <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"959f3344b116927771815235718f3d\">amyloidosis</span> involves protein deposition without significant inflammation.</strong></li>\n</ol>\n\n<p><strong>Other Findings in amyloidosis:</strong></p>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse\">\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Organ </strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Description </strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Kidneys</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Most common and serious <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a1b06f401f1692777203a53393ba98\">form</span> of organ involvement</strong>. <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">Amyloid</span> in arterial/arteriolar walls causes <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0f670d10711692777190af4b12fac9\">ischemia</span> and <strong>kidney shrinkage.</strong></p>\n\n\t\t\t<p>Deposits primarily in glomeruli, leading to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"89e3252d5b16927771833fb9b432ae\">capillary</span> narrowing and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1ad1e71a4a1692777188853097f685\">glomerular</span> obsolescence.</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Liver</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p>Causes moderate to marked hepatomegaly.</p>\n\n\t\t\t<p>Amyloid deposits in the <strong>space of Disse</strong> encroach on <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3268e86ce01692777188f249c64d6e\">hepatic</span> cells and sinusoids, leading to parenchymal replacement.</p>\n\n\t\t\t<p>Liver function is usually preserved despite extensive involvement.</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Heart</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p>Can occur in <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8f2e7fd96116927771995b451b5c90\">systemic</span> or <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f13bb39af816927771989e731b0502\">senile</span> amyloidosis.</p>\n\n\t\t\t<p>Amyloid deposits between <strong>myocardial fibres and subendocardially,</strong> causing pressure <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"97ff5253fb169277718224c7b0faf8\">atrophy</span> and potential ECG abnormalities.</p>\n\n\t\t\t<p>Heart may appear enlarged or firm</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Tongue</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p>Nodular deposits cause macroglossia, known as tumour-forming <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> of the tongue</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Respiratory Tract</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p>Involvement ranges from the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"80452d1746169277719165b097dc7a\">larynx</span> to small bronchioles, either focally or diffusely</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Nerves</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p>Peripheral and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bd1c98736616927771820954b0a744\">autonomic</span> nerve involvement is seen in <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5dda3cc2ab1692777202b3b3c65bea\">familial</span> amyloidotic neuropathies.</p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p>The image below shows a histopathological <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"754ab07a2e1692777183ed178c883d\">biopsy</span> of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b9356afdba16927771979d068c6587\">renal</span> amyloidosis.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"Nephron\" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"CC BY-SA 3.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Renal_amyloidosis_-_2_-_very_high_mag.jpg\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"1107\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/eTVYXSEolEPdYSePrIxN1737015872.png\" width=\"1999\" /></p>",
