      "correct_choice_id": 2,
      "solution": "<p><strong>CORRECT ANSWER:</strong> <strong>C) <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a97f1abe2b1692777185a049d20f07\">Congo red</span> stain</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>EXPLANATION:</strong></p>\n\n<p>The clinical presentation of a patient with poorly controlled diabetes and hypertension, hepatomegaly, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"625feb7e3a1692777183aa9d923cfd\">bilateral</span> lower <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"c8ed8e0fb61692777187c860f7056f\">extremity</span> oedema, proteinuria, and elevated <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1ffaec13de169277719828374cfda0\">serum</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"2ead0fd0301692777185187bd72768\">creatinine</span> highly point towards a diagnosis of <strong>AA amyloidosis</strong>, where <strong>chronic inflammation</strong> leads to the <strong>production of SAA</strong>, resulting in <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> deposition in various organs.</p>\n\n<p>Congo red <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b29a1a16ab1692777199ede1c6e28b\">stain</span> is the most appropriate technique to confirm the diagnosis of amyloidosis.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Investigations in amyloidosis:</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>The diagnosis depends on the <strong>histologic demonstration of amyloid</strong> deposits in tissues.</li>\n\t<li>The most common sites biopsied are the <strong>kidney</strong> when <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"b9356afdba16927771979d068c6587\">renal</span> manifestations are present or rectal or gingival tissues in patients suspected of having <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8f2e7fd96116927771995b451b5c90\">systemic</span> amyloidosis.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Examination of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1665a40f1016927771801899eaed5d\">abdominal</span> fat aspirates</strong> stained with <strong>Congo red</strong> can also be used for the diagnosis of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8f2e7fd96116927771995b451b5c90\">systemic</span> amyloidosis.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<table cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:587px\">\n\t<tbody>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Stains/technique</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Appearance</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Congo red</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Most widely used and specific.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Light microscopy: Salmon pink/red stains.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Polarising microscopy: <strong>Apple-green birefringence.</strong></li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>H & E</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Eosin & <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1cbb322f2c1692777188d48b3e3ef7\">hematoxylin</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3b007026bd16927771997ae809b603\">staining</span> on light microscopy.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li><strong>Amorphous</strong>, <strong>eosinophilic</strong>, <strong>extracellular</strong> substance.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Thioflavin T</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Fluorescent stain.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Yellow colour under UV light.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Electron microscopy</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Non-branching fibrils of indefinite length.</li>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Diameter: 7.5-10 nm.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>X-ray <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1ab23807771692777185b9e3f5a412\">crystallography</span> & <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"82df9c600116927771907b7977a3b4\">infrared</span> spectroscopy</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Cross-β-pleated sheet conformation.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t\t<tr>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Methyl violet</strong></p>\n\n\t\t\t<p><strong>Crystal violet</strong></p>\n\n\t\t\t<p><strong>PAS</strong></p>\n\t\t\t</td>\n\t\t\t<td style=\"border-bottom:1px solid #000000; border-left:1px solid #000000; border-right:1px solid #000000; border-top:1px solid #000000; vertical-align:top\">\n\t\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t\t<li>Amyloid positive.</li>\n\t\t\t</ul>\n\t\t\t<br />\n\t\t\t </td>\n\t\t</tr>\n\t</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Gross <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3b007026bd16927771997ae809b603\">staining</span> by Lugol's <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"58c4fcb71116927771901e83ac026f\">Iodine</span> - Mahogany brown appearance</li>\n\t<li>Abdominal fat <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"831d67ad8a1692777182763ca62e4b\">aspiration</span> is preferred over rectal biopsy.</li>\n\t<li>In suspected cases of AL amyloidosis, <strong>serum, and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"0096f2a7631692777201eb9f21d5a7\">urine</span> protein electrophoresis</strong> and <strong>immunoelectrophoresis</strong> should be performed.</li>\n\t<li>Bone <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"c8a8c935a41692777191610f6aacb4\">marrow</span> aspirates in such cases often show <strong>monoclonal plasmacytosis</strong>, even in the absence of overt multiple myeloma.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Scintigraphy with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7cd1a840a2169277719756692d362d\">radiolabeled</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1ffaec13de169277719828374cfda0\">serum</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> P</strong> component is a <strong>rapid and specific test </strong>since it binds to the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> deposits and reveals their presence.</li>\n\t<li>It also gives a measure of the extent of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"959f3344b116927771815235718f3d\">amyloidosis</span> and can be used to follow patients undergoing treatment.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>The given images below show <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a97f1abe2b1692777185a049d20f07\">Congo red</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"3b007026bd16927771997ae809b603\">staining</span> in amyloidosis.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"Ed Uthman \" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"CC BY 2.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Amyloidosis,_lymph_node,_polarizer.jpg\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"1493\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/SjZsEjDbkkmF3acJ1wwt1737015936.png\" width=\"1999\" /></p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"\" data-author=\"Ed Uthman \" data-hash=\"\" data-license=\"CC BY 2.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Gastric_Amyloidosis_(Congo_Red_Stain)_(3595839154).jpg\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"1693\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/content/SRG51l27K8we2fZ7rGG31737015920.png\" width=\"1999\" /></p>\n\n<p><strong>Periodic acid Schiff (PAS) stain(Option A):</strong> While positive for amyloid, it's not specific and less commonly used for diagnosis.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Masson trichrome stain(Option B):</strong> Primarily used for <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"67e237a57c16927771859803f93ab3\">connective</span> tissue (collagen appears blue, smooth muscles appear red, the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ff628904401692777193c8a9f9159e\">nucleus</span> appears black), not specific for amyloid.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Oil red O(Option D): </strong>Used for lipids, not applicable for <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"51ad856e041692777181f80c9d507a\">amyloid</span> detection.</p>\n\n<p> </p>",
